{"title_page": "Just-world hypothesis", "text_new": "The '''just-world fallacy''' or '''just-world hypothesis''' is the [[cognitive bias]] (or assumption) that a person's actions are inherently inclined to bring [[morality|morally]] [[justice|fair]] and fitting consequences to that person, to the end of all noble actions being eventually rewarded and all evil actions eventually punished. In other words, the just-world hypothesis is the tendency to attribute consequences to\u2014or expect consequences as the result of\u2014a universal force that restores moral balance. This belief generally implies the existence of cosmic [[justice]], [[destiny]], [[divine providence]], [[desert (philosophy)|desert]], [[Balance (metaphysics)|stability]], and/or [[cosmos|order]], and is often associated with a variety of fundamental [[informal fallacy|fallacies]], especially in regard to [[Rationalization (making excuses)|rationalizing]] people's suffering on the grounds that they \"deserve\" it.\n\nThe hypothesis popularly appears in the [[English language]] in various [[figures of speech]] that imply guaranteed negative reprisal, such as: \"[[wikt:get what's coming to one|you got what was coming to you]]\", \"[[wikt:what goes around comes around|what goes around comes around]]\", \"[[wikt:chickens come home to roost|chickens come home to roost]]\", \"everything happens for a reason\", and \"[[wikt:reap what one sows|you reap what you sow]]\". This hypothesis has been widely studied by [[social psychology|social psychologists]] since [[Melvin J. Lerner]] conducted seminal work on the belief in a just world in the early 1960s.<ref name=\"An Overview\">{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_1 | chapter=An Overview: Advances in Belief in a Just World Theory and Methods| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=1\u20137| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Lerner| first1=Melvin J.| last2=Montada| first2=Leo| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> Research has continued since then, examining the predictive capacity of the hypothesis in various situations and across cultures, and clarifying and expanding the theoretical understandings of just-world beliefs.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\">{{cite journal|title=Belief in a just world: research progress over the past decade|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|volume=34|issue=5|pages=795\u2013817|doi=10.1016/S0191-8869(02)00072-7|year=2003|last1=Furnham|first1=Adrian}}</ref>\n\n==Emergence==\nMany philosophers and social theorists have observed and considered the phenomenon of belief in a just world, going back to at least as early as the [[Pyrrhonism|Pyrrhonist]] philosopher [[Sextus Empiricus]], writing ''circa'' 180 CE, who argued against this belief.<ref>Sextus Empiricus, \"Outlines of Pyrrhonism\", Book 1, Chapter 13, Section 32</ref> Lerner's work made the just-world hypothesis a focus of research in the field of social psychology.\n\n===Melvin Lerner===\n[[Melvin Lerner|Lerner]] was prompted to study [[Justice|justice]] beliefs and the just-world hypothesis in the context of social psychological inquiry into negative social and societal interactions.<ref name=\"MontadaLernerPreface\">{{cite book |chapter=Preface|pp= vii\u2013viii|last=Montada |first=Leo |last2=Lerner |first2=Melvin J. |year=1998 |title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World |series=Critical Issues in Social Justice |isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum|chapter-url=https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/bfm%3A978-1-4757-6418-5%2F1.pdf}}</ref> Lerner saw his work as extending [[Stanley Milgram]]'s [[Milgram experiments|work on obedience]]. He sought to answer the questions of how regimes that cause cruelty and suffering maintain popular support, and how people come to accept [[Social norm|social norms]] and laws that produce misery and suffering.<ref name=\"LernerSimmonsObserver\">{{cite journal |last=Lerner |first=M. |last2=Simmons |first2=C. H. |year=1966 |title=Observer's Reaction to the 'Innocent Victim': Compassion or Rejection? |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=203\u2013210 |doi=10.1037/h0023562 |pmid=5969146 |url=http://web.mit.edu/curhan/www/docs/Articles/biases/4_J_Personality_Social_Psychology_203_(Lerner).pdf}}</ref>\n\nLerner's inquiry was influenced by repeatedly witnessing the tendency of observers to [[victim blaming|blame victims]] for their suffering. During his clinical training as a psychologist, he observed treatment of mentally ill persons by the health care practitioners with whom he worked. Although Lerner knew them to be kindhearted, educated people, they often blamed patients for the patients' own suffering.<ref name=\"LernerFundamental\">{{cite book |last=Lerner |first=Melvin J. |year=1980 |title=The Belief in a Just World: A Fundamental Delusion |series=Perspectives in Social Psychology |location=New York |publisher=Plenum Press |isbn=978-0-306-40495-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4899-0448-5}}</ref> Lerner also describes his surprise at hearing his students [[wikt:derogate|derogate]] (disparage, belittle) the poor, seemingly oblivious to the [[structural violence|structural forces]] that contribute to poverty.<ref name=\"MontadaLernerPreface\" /> In a study on rewards, he observed that when one of two men was chosen at random to receive a reward for a task, that caused him to be more favorably evaluated by observers, even when the observers had been informed that the recipient of the reward was chosen at random.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0033-2909.85.5.1030 | title=Just world research and the attribution process: Looking back and ahead| journal=Psychological Bulletin| volume=85| issue=5| pages=1030\u20131051| year=1978| last1=Lerner| first1=Melvin J.| last2=Miller| first2=Dale T.}}</ref><ref name=\"MaesEightStages\" /> Existing social psychological theories, including [[cognitive dissonance]], could not fully explain these phenomena.<ref name=\"MaesEightStages\">{{Cite book |doi = 10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_10|chapter = Eight Stages in the Development of Research on the Construct of Belief in a Just World?|title = Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World|pages = 163\u2013185|series = Critical Issues in Social Justice|year = 1998|last1 = Maes|first1 = J\u00fcrgen|isbn = 978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> The desire to understand the processes that caused these phenomena led Lerner to conduct his first experiments on what is now called the just-world hypothesis.\n\n==Early evidence==\nIn 1966, Lerner and his colleagues began a series of experiments that used shock paradigms to investigate observer responses to [[victimization]]. In the first of these experiments conducted at the [[University of Kansas]], 72 female participants watched what appeared to be a confederate receiving electrical shocks under a variety of conditions. Initially, these observing participants were upset by the victim's apparent suffering. But as the suffering continued and observers remained unable to intervene, the observers began to reject and devalue the victim. Rejection and devaluation of the victim was greater when the observed suffering was greater. But when participants were told the victim would receive compensation for her suffering, the participants did not derogate the victim.<ref name=\"LernerSimmonsObserver\" /> Lerner and colleagues replicated these findings in subsequent studies, as did other researchers.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\" />\n\n==Theory==\nTo explain these studies' findings, Lerner theorized that there was a prevalent belief in a just world. A just world is one in which actions and conditions have predictable, appropriate consequences. These actions and conditions are typically individuals' behaviors or attributes. The specific conditions that correspond to certain consequences are socially determined by a society's norms and ideologies. Lerner presents the belief in a just world as functional: it maintains the idea that one can influence the world in a predictable way. Belief in a just world functions as a sort of \"contract\" with the world regarding the consequences of behavior. This allows people to plan for the future and engage in effective, goal-driven behavior. Lerner summarized his findings and his theoretical work in his 1980 monograph ''The Belief in a Just World: A Fundamental Delusion''.<ref name=\"LernerFundamental\" />\n\nLerner hypothesized that the belief in a just world is crucially important for people to maintain for their own well-being. But people are confronted daily with evidence that the world is not just: people suffer without apparent cause. Lerner explained that people use strategies to eliminate threats to their belief in a just world. These strategies can be [[Rationality|rational]] or irrational. Rational strategies include accepting the reality of injustice, trying to prevent injustice or provide restitution, and accepting one's own limitations. Non-rational strategies include [[denial]], [[Social withdrawal|withdrawal]], and [[Rationalization (making excuses)|reinterpretation]] of the event.<ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1017/CBO9780511499975.008|chapter = Helping and Rationalization as Alternative Strategies for Restoring the Belief in a Just World: Evidence from Longitudinal Change Analyses|title = The Justice Motive in Everyday Life|pages = 127\u2013148|year = 2002|last1 = Reichle|first1 = Barbara|last2 = Schmitt|first2 = Manfred|isbn = 9780511499975|editor-last=Ross |editor-first=Michael |editor-last2=Miller |editor-first2=Dale T. |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref> \n\nThere are a few modes of reinterpretation that could make an event fit the belief in a just world. One can reinterpret the outcome, the cause, and/or the character of the victim.  In the case of observing the injustice of the suffering of innocent people, one major way to rearrange the cognition of an event is to interpret the victim of suffering as deserving.<ref name=\"An Overview\" /> Specifically, observers can blame victims for their suffering on the basis of their behaviors and/or their characteristics.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\" /> Much psychological research on the belief in a just world has focused on these negative social phenomena of [[victim blaming]] and victim derogation in [[#Additional evidence|different contexts]].<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" />\n\nAn additional effect of this thinking is that individuals experience less personal [[vulnerability]] because they do not believe they have done anything to deserve or cause negative outcomes.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /> This is related to the [[self-serving bias]] observed by social psychologists.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FCdQlTzL-aUC |title = Embitterment: Societal, psychological, and clinical perspectives|isbn = 9783211997413|last1 = Linden|first1 = Michael|last2 = Maercker|first2 = Andreas|date = 2011|location=Wien|publisher=Springer}}</ref>\n\nMany researchers have interpreted just-world beliefs as an example of [[causal attribution]]. In victim blaming, the causes of victimization are attributed to an individual rather than to a situation. Thus, the consequences of belief in a just world may be related to or explained in terms of particular patterns of causal attribution.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.47.3.494 |title = Societal influences on attribution: Blaming some victims more than others|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 47|issue = 3|pages = 494\u2013505|year = 1984|last1 = Howard|first1 = Judith A.}}</ref>\n\n==Alternatives==\n\n===Veridical judgment===\n{{See also|Veridicality}}\nOthers have suggested alternative explanations for the derogation of victims. One suggestion is that derogation effects are based on accurate judgments of a victim's character. In particular, in relation to Lerner's first studies, some have hypothesized that it would be logical for observers to derogate an individual who would allow himself to be shocked without reason.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/h0076786 |title = Devaluation of innocent victims: An attribution analysis within the just world paradigm|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 31|issue = 5|pages = 944\u2013951|year = 1975|last1 = Godfrey|first1 = Bruce W.|last2 = Lowe|first2 = Charles A.}}</ref> A subsequent study by Lerner challenged this alternative hypothesis by showing that individuals are only derogated when they actually suffer; individuals who agreed to undergo suffering but did not were viewed positively.<ref>Lerner, M.J. (1970). The desire for justice and reactions to victims. In J. Macaulay & L. Berkowitz (Eds.), ''Altruism and helping behavior'' (pp. 205\u2013229). New York: Academic Press.</ref>\n\n===Guilt reduction===\nAnother alternative explanation offered for the derogation of victims early in the development of the just-world hypothesis was that observers derogate victims to reduce their own feelings of [[guilt (emotion)|guilt]]. Observers may feel [[Moral responsibility|responsible]], or guilty, for a victim's suffering if they themselves are involved in the situation or experiment. In order to reduce the guilt, they may devalue the victim.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/h0044214 |pmid = 13720212|title = Changes in interpersonal perception as a means of reducing cognitive dissonance|journal = The Journal of Abnormal and Social Psychology|volume = 61|issue = 3|pages = 402\u2013410|year = 1960|last1 = Davis|first1 = Keith E.|last2 = Jones|first2 = Edward E.|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b99153d1428be3bc352ded10335cedc420fb84eb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1467-6494.1964.tb01357.x |pmid = 14238983|title = Changes in liking as a means of reducing cognitive discrepancies between self-esteem and aggression|journal = Journal of Personality|volume = 32|issue = 4|pages = 531\u2013549|year = 1964|last1 = Glass|first1 = David C.|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/37b14d60470b29c030ac7f116cf422e97475a1c6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.33.6.719 |title = Victim derogation in the Lerner paradigm: Just world or just justification?|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 33|issue = 6|pages = 719\u2013724|year = 1976|last1 = Cialdini|first1 = Robert B.|last2 = Kenrick|first2 = Douglas T.|last3 = Hoerig|first3 = James H.}}</ref> Lerner and colleagues claim that there has not been adequate evidence to support this interpretation. They conducted one study that found derogation of victims occurred even by observers who were not implicated in the process of the experiment and thus had no reason to feel guilty.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\" />\n\n===Discomfort reduction===\n\nAlternatively, victim derogation and other strategies may only be ways to alleviate discomfort after viewing suffering. This would mean that the primary motivation is not to restore a belief in a just world, but to reduce discomfort caused by [[empathy|empathizing]].  Studies have shown that victim derogation does not suppress subsequent helping activity and that empathizing with the victim plays a large role when assigning blame. According to [[Ervin Staub]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Staub|first1=Ervin|title=Positive Social Behavior and Morality: Social and Personal Influences, Volume 1|date=1978|publisher=Academic Press Inc.|isbn=978-0-12-663101-2|pages=169\u2013170|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GiOLBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA169&lpg=PA169&q=reduce%20discomfort%20suffering%20erwin%20just%20world}}</ref> devaluing the victim should lead to lesser compensation if restoring belief in a just world was the primary motive; instead, there is virtually no difference in compensation amounts whether the compensation precedes or follows devaluation. [[Psychopathy]] has been linked to the lack of just-world maintaining strategies, possibly due to dampened emotional reactions and lack of empathy.<ref name=\"Hafer2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Hafer |first1=Carolyn L. |last2=B\u00e8gue |first2=Laurent |last3=Choma |first3=Becky L. |last4=Dempsey |first4=Julie L. |title=Belief in a Just World and Commitment to Long-Term Deserved Outcomes |journal=Social Justice Research |date=2005 |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=429\u2013444 |doi=10.1007/s11211-005-8569-3 |url=http://www.lps.univ-savoie.fr/uploads/PDF/576.pdf  |citeseerx=10.1.1.507.4227 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228091123/http://www.lps.univ-savoie.fr/uploads/PDF/576.pdf |archive-date=2013-12-28 }}</ref>\n\n==Additional evidence==\nAfter Lerner's first studies, other researchers replicated these findings in other settings in which individuals are victimized. This work, which began in the 1970s and continues today, has investigated how observers react to victims of random calamities like traffic accidents, as well as rape and [[domestic violence]], illnesses, and poverty.<ref name=\"An Overview\" /> Generally, researchers have found that observers of the suffering of innocent victims tend to both derogate and blame victims for their suffering. Observers thus maintain their belief in a just world by changing their cognitions about the victims' character.<ref>{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_4 | chapter=How do Observers of Victimization Preserve Their Belief in a Just World Cognitively or Actionally?| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=55\u201364| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Reichle| first1=Barbara| last2=Schneider| first2=Angela| last3=Montada| first3=Leo| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s, social psychologists [[Zick Rubin]] and Letitia Anne Peplau developed a measure of belief in a just world.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1973.tb00104.x |title = Belief in a Just World and Reactions to Another's Lot: A Study of Participants in the National Draft Lottery|journal = Journal of Social Issues|volume = 29|issue = 4|pages = 73\u201393|year = 1973|last1 = Rubin|first1 = Zick|last2 = Peplau|first2 = Anne}}</ref> This measure and its revised form published in 1975 allowed for the study of individual differences in just-world beliefs.<ref name = \"RubinPeplau1975\">{{cite journal|last=Rubin |first=Z. |last2=Peplau |first2=L. A. |year=1975  |title=Who believes in a just world? |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=65\u201390 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1975.tb00997.x |url=http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073011/http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 }}</ref> Much of the subsequent research on the just-world hypothesis used these [[psychometrics|measurement scales]].\n\nThese studies on victims of [[#Violence|violence]], [[#Illness|illness]], and [[#Poverty|poverty]] and others like them have provided consistent support for the link between observers' just-world beliefs and their tendency to blame victims for their suffering.<ref name=\"An Overview\" /> As a result, the existence of the just-world hypothesis as a psychological phenomenon has become widely accepted.\n\n===Violence===\nResearchers have looked at how observers react to victims of [[rape]] and other [[violence]]. In a formative experiment on rape and belief in a just world by Linda Carli and colleagues, researchers gave two groups of subjects a narrative about interactions between a man and a woman. The description of the interaction was the same until the end; one group received a narrative that had a neutral ending and the other group received a narrative that ended with the man raping the woman. Subjects judged the rape ending as inevitable and blamed the woman in the narrative for the rape on the basis of her behavior, but not her characteristics.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/0022-1031(85)90013-7 |title = Cognitive biases in blaming the victim|journal = Journal of Experimental Social Psychology|volume = 21|issue = 2|pages = 161\u2013177|year = 1985|last1 = Janoff-Bulman|first1 = Ronnie|last2 = Timko|first2 = Christine|last3 = Carli|first3 = Linda L.|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/223081344}}</ref> These findings have been replicated repeatedly, including using a rape ending and a 'happy ending' (a marriage proposal).<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/01461672992511005 |title = Cognitive Reconstruction, Hindsight, and Reactions to Victims and Perpetrators|journal = Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin|volume = 25|issue = 8|pages = 966\u2013979|year = 1999|last1 = Carli|first1 = Linda L.|citeseerx = 10.1.1.830.8628}}</ref>\n\nOther researchers have found a similar phenomenon for judgments of [[domestic violence|battered partners]]. One study found that observers' labels of blame of female victims of relationship violence increase with the intimacy of the relationship. Observers blamed the perpetrator only in the most significant{{what|date=March 2019}} case of violence, in which a male struck an acquaintance.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1521/jscp.1984.2.4.339|title = Blaming the Victim Versus Blaming the Perpetrator: An Attributional Analysis of Spouse Abuse|journal = Journal of Social and Clinical Psychology|volume = 2|issue = 4|pages = 339\u2013347|year = 1984|last1 = Summers|first1 = Gertrude|last2 = Feldman|first2 = Nina S.}}</ref>\n\n===Bullying===\nResearchers have employed the just-world hypothesis to understand [[bullying]]. Given other research on beliefs in a just world, it would be expected that observers would derogate and blame bullying victims, but the opposite has been found: individuals high in just-world belief have stronger anti-bullying [[Attitude (psychology)|attitudes]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1348/000709909X479105 | pmid=19930790| title=The association between adolescents' beliefs in a just world and their attitudes to victims of bullying| journal=British Journal of Educational Psychology| volume=80| issue=2| pages=183\u2013198| year=2010| last1=Fox| first1=Claire L.| last2=Elder| first2=Tracey.| last3=Gater| first3=Josephine| last4=Johnson| first4=Elizabeth| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3f6e30cf501a02993d86777c4046f1ae0f1541a3}}</ref> Other researchers have found that strong belief in a just world is associated with lower levels of bullying behavior.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1027/1016-9040.13.4.248 |title = School Bullying|journal = European Psychologist|volume = 13|issue = 4|pages = 248\u2013254|year = 2008|last1 = Correia|first1 = Isabel|last2 = Dalbert|first2 = Claudia|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1711694294eef21252ec6d5e3402a556cd25caea}}</ref> This finding is in keeping with Lerner's understanding of belief in a just world as functioning as a \"contract\" that governs behavior.<ref name=\"LernerFundamental\" /> There is additional evidence that belief in a just world is protective of the well-being of children and adolescents in the school environment,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/10615800902729242 |pmid = 19333798|title = Belief in a just world and well-being of bullies, victims and defenders: A study with Portuguese and Indian students|journal = Anxiety, Stress & Coping|volume = 22|issue = 5|pages = 497\u2013508|year = 2009|last1 = Correia|first1 = Isabel|last2 = Kamble|first2 = Shanmukh V.|last3 = Dalbert|first3 = Claudia|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ca1d145496d3740b12fdba4f2b406a7bc173d5f6}}</ref> as has been shown for the [[#Positive health effects|general population]].\n\n===Illness===\nOther researchers have found that observers judge sick people as responsible for their illnesses. One experiment showed that persons suffering from a variety of illnesses were derogated on a measure of attractiveness more than healthy individuals were. In comparison to healthy people, victim derogation was found for persons presenting with indigestion, pneumonia, and stomach cancer. Moreover, derogation was found to be higher for those suffering from more severe illnesses, except for those presenting with cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1207/s15324834basp0401_4 | title=Disease as Justice: Perceptions of the Victims of Physical Illness| journal=Basic and Applied Social Psychology| volume=4| pages=39\u201346| year=1983| last1=Gruman| first1=Jessie C.| last2=Sloan| first2=Richard P.}}</ref> Stronger belief in a just world has also been found to correlate with greater derogation of [[AIDS]] victims.<ref name=\"FurnhamProcterAIDS\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/001872679204500303 |title = Sphere-Specific Just World Beliefs and Attitudes to AIDS|journal = Human Relations|volume = 45|issue = 3|pages = 265\u2013280|year = 1992|last1 = Furnham|first1 = Adrian|last2 = Procter|first2 = Eddie}}</ref>\n\n===Poverty===\nMore recently, researchers have explored how people react to [[poverty]] through the lens of the just-world hypothesis. Strong belief in a just world is associated with blaming the poor, with weak belief in a just world associated with identifying external causes of poverty including world economic systems, [[war]], and [[Exploitation of labour|exploitation]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.2224/sbp.1990.18.2.235 |title = Lay Causal Perceptions of Third World Poverty and the Just World Theory'|journal = Social Behavior and Personality: An International Journal|volume = 18|issue = 2|pages = 235\u2013238|year = 1990|last1 = Harper|first1 = David J.|last2 = Wagstaff|first2 = Graham F.|last3 = Newton|first3 = J. Tim|last4 = Harrison|first4 = Kevin R.|url=http://inesad.edu.bo/developmentroast/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Harper-1990-Poverty-Explanations.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00224545.1992.9712107 |title = The Just World and the Third World: British explanations for poverty abroad|journal = The Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 132|issue = 6|pages = 783\u2013785|year = 1992|last1 = Harper|first1 = David J.|last2 = Manasse|first2 = Paul R.|url=http://psycnet.apa.org/record/1993-29152-001}}</ref>\n\n===The self as victim===\n{{See also|Psychological response to rape|Self blame}}\nSome research on belief in a just world has examined how people react when they themselves are victimized. An early paper by Dr. Ronnie Janoff-Bulman found that rape victims often blame their own behavior, but not their own characteristics, for their [[victimization]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.37.10.1798 |pmid = 512837|title = Characterological versus behavioral self-blame: Inquiries into depression and rape|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 37|issue = 10|pages = 1798\u20131809|year = 1979|last1 = Janoff-Bulman|first1 = Ronnie|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cf8f4a1d49479660a825c1ba138b88c5054c9b83}}</ref> It was hypothesized that this may be because blaming one's own behavior makes an event more [[locus of control|controllable]].\n\n==Theoretical refinement==\nSubsequent work on measuring belief in a just world has focused on identifying multiple dimensions of the belief. This work has resulted in the development of new measures of just-world belief and additional research.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /> Hypothesized dimensions of just-world beliefs include belief in an unjust world,<ref>{{cite journal|title= A just and unjust world: Structure and validity of different world beliefs|journal= Personality and Individual Differences|volume= 30|issue= 4|pages= 561\u2013577|doi= 10.1016/S0191-8869(00)00055-6|year= 2001|last1= Dalbert|first1= C.|last2= Lipkus|first2= I.|last3= Sallay|first3= H.|last4= Goch|first4= I.}}</ref> beliefs in [[immanent]] [[justice]] and ultimate justice,<ref>{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_2 | chapter=Immanent justice and ultimate justice: two ways of believing in justice| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=9\u201340| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Maes| first1=J\u00fcrgen| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> hope for justice, and belief in one's ability to reduce injustice.<ref>{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_3 | chapter=BJW and Self-Efficacy in Coping with Observed Victimization| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=41\u201354| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Mohiyeddini| first1=Changiz| last2=Montada| first2=Leo| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref>  Other work has focused on looking at the different domains in which the belief may function; individuals may have different just-world beliefs for the personal domain, the sociopolitical domain, the social domain, etc.<ref name=\"FurnhamProcterAIDS\" /> An especially fruitful distinction is between the belief in a just world for the self (personal) and the belief in a just world for others (general). These distinct beliefs are differentially associated with [[Just-world hypothesis#Positive mental health effects|positive mental health]].<ref name=\"Lipkusetal\" />\n\n==Correlates==\nResearchers have used measures of [[belief]] in a just world to look at correlates of high and low levels of belief in a just world.\n\nLimited studies have examined ideological correlates of the belief in a just world. These studies have found sociopolitical correlates of just-world beliefs, including [[right-wing authoritarianism]] and the [[Protestant work ethic]].{{fix|text=a positive or negative correlation?}}<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/0146167299025006001 | title=Perceptions of Risk and the Buffering Hypothesis: The Role of Just World Beliefs and Right-Wing Authoritarianism| journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin| volume=25| issue=6| pages=643\u2013656| year=1999| last1=Lambert| first1=Alan J.| last2=Burroughs| first2=Thomas| last3=Nguyen| first3=Tina| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/12cd89f3fdf3c59dbaf14f6c746a69be7296e76b}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.2044-8309.1989.tb00880.x |title = Belief in a just world: Review and critique of the individual difference literature|journal = British Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 28|issue = 4|pages = 365\u2013384|year = 1989|last1 = Furnham|first1 = Adrian|last2 = Procter|first2 = Edward}}</ref> Studies have also found belief in a just world to be correlated with aspects of [[religiousness]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Beliefs in justice and faith in people: just world, religiosity and interpersonal trust|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|volume=32|issue=3|pages=375\u2013382|doi=10.1016/S0191-8869(00)00224-5|year=2002|last1=B\u00e8gue|first1=Laurent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kunst |first=J. L. |last2=Bjorck |first2=J. P. |last3=Tan |first3=S.-Y. |year=2000 |title=Causal attributions for uncontrollable negative events |url=http://psycnet.apa.org/record/2000-07654-003 |journal=Journal of Psychology and Christianity |volume=19 |issue=1 |pp=47\u201360}}</ref>\n\nStudies of demographic differences, including [[gender]] and [[Race (classification of humans)|racial]] differences, have not shown systemic differences, but do suggest racial differences, with blacks and African Americans having the lowest levels of belief in a just world.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00224545.1994.9923011 |title = Differences in Assumptions about a Just World: Ethnicity and Point of View|journal = The Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 134|issue = 6|pages = 765\u2013770|year = 1994|last1 = Calhoun|first1 = Lawrence G.|last2 = Cann|first2 = Arnie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 42864385|title = Status, Religion, and the \"Belief in a Just World\": Comparing African Americans, Latinos, and Whites|journal = Social Science Quarterly|volume = 81|issue = 1|pages = 325\u2013343|last1 = Hunt|first1 = Matthew O.|year = 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe development of measures of just-world beliefs has also allowed researchers to assess cross-cultural differences in just-world beliefs. Much research conducted shows that beliefs in a just world are evident cross-culturally. One study tested beliefs in a just world of students in 12 countries. This study found that in countries where the majority of inhabitants are powerless, belief in a just world tends to be weaker than in other countries.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00224545.1993.9712149 |title = Just World Beliefs in Twelve Societies|journal = The Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 133|issue = 3|pages = 317\u2013329|year = 1993|last1 = Furnham|first1 = Adrian}}</ref> This supports the theory of the just-world hypothesis because the powerless have had more personal and societal experiences that provided evidence that the world is not just and predictable.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.2466/pr0.1992.71.3f.1149 | pmid=1480694| title=Relationship between Knowledge of and Attitudes towards Aids| journal=Psychological Reports| volume=71| issue=3_suppl| pages=1149\u20131150| year=1992| last1=Furnham| first1=Adrian}}</ref>{{Clarify|reason=I assume you mean to say 'neither just nor predictable.'|date=February 2014}}\n\nBelief in unjust world has been linked to increased [[self-handicapping]], criminality, defensive coping, anger and perceived future risk. It{{what|date=March 2019}} may also serve as ego-protective belief for certain individuals by justifying maladaptive behavior.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lench|first1=Chang|title=Belief in an Unjust World: When Beliefs in a Just World Fail|journal=Journal of Personality Assessment|date=2007|volume=89|issue=2|pages=126\u2013135|doi=10.1080/00223890701468477|pmid=17764390|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a87debcbbdcf9b0d62b160f657ed1d09ff280581}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dolinski|first1=Dariusz|title=The belief in an unjust world: An egotistic delusion|journal=Social Justice Research|date=1996|volume=9|issue=3|pages=213\u2013221|doi=10.1007/BF02197248}}</ref>\n\n==Current research==\n\n===Positive mental health effects===\nAlthough much of the initial work on belief in a just world focused on its negative social effects, other research suggests that belief in a just world is good, and even necessary, for [[mental health]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sbKCnhCPaSgC&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q=%22The%20justice%20motive%20as%20a%20personal%20resource%3A%20dealing%20with%20challenges%20and%20critical%20life%20events%22 |title = The Justice Motive as a Personal Resource: Dealing with Challenges and Critical Life Events|isbn = 9780306465550|last1 = Dalbert|first1 = Claudia|date = 2001|location=New York |publisher=Plenum}}</ref> Belief in a just world is associated with greater [[life satisfaction]] and well-being and less depressive affect.<ref name=\"Lipkusetal\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/0146167296227002 | title=The Importance of Distinguishing the Belief in a Just World for Self Versus for Others: Implications for Psychological Well-Being| journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin| volume=22| issue=7| pages=666\u2013677| year=1996| last1=Lipkus| first1=Isaac M.| last2=Dalbert| first2=Claudia| last3=Siegler| first3=Ilene C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.2307/1389045 | jstor=1389045| title=Belief in a Just World and Depression| journal=Sociological Perspectives| volume=33| issue=2| pages=235\u2013252| year=1990| last1=Ritter| first1=Christian| last2=Benson| first2=D. E.| last3=Synder| first3=Clint}}</ref> Researchers are actively exploring the reasons why the belief in a just world might have this relationship to mental health; it has been suggested that such beliefs could be a personal resource or [[coping (psychology)|coping strategy]] that buffers [[Stress (psychological)|stress]] associated with daily life and with [[psychological trauma|traumatic events]].<ref name = \"HaferinMontadaLerner\">{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_5 | chapter=Individual Differences in the Belief in a Just World and Responses to Personal Misfortune| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=65\u201386| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Hafer| first1=Carolyn L.| last2=Olson| first2=James M.| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> This hypothesis suggests that belief in a just world can be understood as a [[positive illusion]].<ref>{{Cite journal |pmid = 3283814|year = 1988|last1 = Taylor|first1 = S. E.|title = Illusion and well-being: A social psychological perspective on mental health|journal = Psychological Bulletin|volume = 103|issue = 2|pages = 193\u2013210|last2 = Brown|first2 = J. D.|doi = 10.1037/0033-2909.103.2.193|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/16c6b13d227783a3466d7a0903d9ebb111904502}}</ref>\n\nSome studies also show that beliefs in a just world are correlated with internal [[locus of control]].<ref name=\"RubinPeplau1975\" /> Strong belief in a just world is associated with greater acceptance of and less dissatisfaction with negative events in one's life.<ref name = \"HaferinMontadaLerner\" /> This may be one way in which belief in a just world affects mental health. Others have suggested that this relationship holds only for beliefs in a just world for oneself. Beliefs in a just world for others are related instead to the negative social phenomena of victim blaming and victim derogation observed in other studies.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Justice for all, or just for me? More evidence of the importance of the self-other distinction in just-world beliefs|journal= Personality and Individual Differences|volume= 39|issue= 3|pages= 637\u2013645|doi= 10.1016/j.paid.2005.02.010|year= 2005|last1= Sutton|first1= Robbie M.|last2= Douglas|first2= Karen M.}}</ref>\n\n===International research===\nMore than 40 years after Lerner's seminal work on belief in a just world, researchers continue to study the phenomenon. Work continues primarily in the United States, Europe, Australia, and Asia.<ref name=\"MaesEightStages\" /> Researchers in Germany have contributed disproportionately to recent research.<ref name=\"MontadaLernerPreface\" /> Their work resulted in a volume edited by Lerner and German researcher Leo Montada titled [[#CITEREFMontadaLerner1998|''Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World'' (1998)]].\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*\"[[Best of all possible worlds]]\"\n**[[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]]\n**''[[Candide]]''\n**[[Problem of evil]]\n*[[Denial]]\n*[[Fundamental attribution error]]\n*[[Hindsight bias]]\n*{{sectionlink|Karma|Comparable concepts}}\n*[[Mean world syndrome]]\n*[[Moral panic]]\n*[[Natural disasters as divine retribution]]\n*[[Revenge]]\n*[[System justification]]\n*[[The banality of evil]]\n*[[Theodicy]]\n*[[Victim blaming]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Hafer |first=C. L. |last2=B\u00e8gue |first2=L.|year=2005 |title=Experimental research on just-world theory: problems, developments, and future challenges |journal=Psychological Bulletin |volume=131 |issue=1 |pages=128\u2013167 |doi=10.1037/0033-2909.131.1.128 |pmid=15631556 |citeseerx=10.1.1.524.1990 }}\n*{{cite book|doi=10.1016/bs.aesp.2014.09.001|chapter=The Why and How of Defending Belief in a Just World|volume=51|pages=41\u201396|title=Advances in Experimental Social Psychology|year=2015|last1=Hafer|first1=Carolyn L.|last2=Rubel|first2=Alicia N.|isbn=9780128022740}}\n*{{cite book |last=Lerner |first=Melvin J. |year=1980 |title=The Belief in a Just World: A Fundamental Delusion |series=Perspectives in Social Psychology |location=New York |publisher=Plenum Press |isbn=978-0-306-40495-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4899-0448-5}}\n*{{cite book |last=Montada |first=Leo |last2=Lerner |first2=Melvin J. |year=1998 |title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World |series=Critical Issues in Social Justice |isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5|location=New York|publisher=Plenum| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Rubin |first=Z. |last2=Peplau |first2=L. A. |year=1975  |title=Who believes in a just world? |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=65\u201390 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1975.tb00997.x |url=http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073011/http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 }} Reprinted (1977) in Reflections, XII(1), 1\u201326.\n*{{cite journal|last=Rubin |first=Z. |last2=Peplau |first2=L. A. |year=1973 |title=Belief in a just world and reactions to another's lot: A study of participants in the national draft lottery |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=73\u201394 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1973.tb00104.x |url=http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin_Peplau_73.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073030/http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin_Peplau_73.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.units.muohio.edu/psybersite/justworld/index.shtml The Just World Hypothesis]\n*[http://www.scu.edu/ethics/publications/iie/v3n2/justworld.html Issues in Ethics: The Just World Theory]\n\n{{Abuse}}\n{{Biases}}\n{{Bullying}}\n{{Informal fallacy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Just-World Phenomenon}}\n[[Category:Cognitive biases]]\n[[Category:Justice]]\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Conceptual models]]\n[[Category:Hypotheses]]\n[[Category:Abuse]]\n[[Category:Error]]\n[[Category:Ignorance]]\n[[Category:Moral psychology]]\n[[Category:Psychological abuse]]\n[[Category:Informal fallacies]]\n[[Category:Causal fallacies]]\n", "text_old": "The '''just-world hypothesis''' or '''just-world fallacy''' is the [[cognitive bias]] (or assumption) that a person's actions are inherently inclined to bring [[morality|morally]] [[justice|fair]] and fitting consequences to that person, to the end of all noble actions being eventually rewarded and all evil actions eventually punished. In other words, the just-world hypothesis is the tendency to attribute consequences to\u2014or expect consequences as the result of\u2014a universal force that restores moral balance. This belief generally implies the existence of cosmic [[justice]], [[destiny]], [[divine providence]], [[desert (philosophy)|desert]], [[Balance (metaphysics)|stability]], and/or [[cosmos|order]], and is often associated with a variety of fundamental [[informal fallacy|fallacies]], especially in regard to [[Rationalization (making excuses)|rationalizing]] people's suffering on the grounds that they \"deserve\" it.\n\nThe hypothesis popularly appears in the [[English language]] in various [[figures of speech]] that imply guaranteed negative reprisal, such as: \"[[wikt:get what's coming to one|you got what was coming to you]]\", \"[[wikt:what goes around comes around|what goes around comes around]]\", \"[[wikt:chickens come home to roost|chickens come home to roost]]\", \"everything happens for a reason\", and \"[[wikt:reap what one sows|you reap what you sow]]\". This hypothesis has been widely studied by [[social psychology|social psychologists]] since [[Melvin J. Lerner]] conducted seminal work on the belief in a just world in the early 1960s.<ref name=\"An Overview\">{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_1 | chapter=An Overview: Advances in Belief in a Just World Theory and Methods| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=1\u20137| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Lerner| first1=Melvin J.| last2=Montada| first2=Leo| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> Research has continued since then, examining the predictive capacity of the hypothesis in various situations and across cultures, and clarifying and expanding the theoretical understandings of just-world beliefs.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\">{{cite journal|title=Belief in a just world: research progress over the past decade|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|volume=34|issue=5|pages=795\u2013817|doi=10.1016/S0191-8869(02)00072-7|year=2003|last1=Furnham|first1=Adrian}}</ref>\n\n==Emergence==\nMany philosophers and social theorists have observed and considered the phenomenon of belief in a just world, going back to at least as early as the [[Pyrrhonism|Pyrrhonist]] philosopher [[Sextus Empiricus]], writing ''circa'' 180 CE, who argued against this belief.<ref>Sextus Empiricus, \"Outlines of Pyrrhonism\", Book 1, Chapter 13, Section 32</ref> Lerner's work made the just-world hypothesis a focus of research in the field of social psychology.\n\n===Melvin Lerner===\n[[Melvin Lerner|Lerner]] was prompted to study [[Justice|justice]] beliefs and the just-world hypothesis in the context of social psychological inquiry into negative social and societal interactions.<ref name=\"MontadaLernerPreface\">{{cite book |chapter=Preface|pp= vii\u2013viii|last=Montada |first=Leo |last2=Lerner |first2=Melvin J. |year=1998 |title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World |series=Critical Issues in Social Justice |isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum|chapter-url=https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/bfm%3A978-1-4757-6418-5%2F1.pdf}}</ref> Lerner saw his work as extending [[Stanley Milgram]]'s [[Milgram experiments|work on obedience]]. He sought to answer the questions of how regimes that cause cruelty and suffering maintain popular support, and how people come to accept [[Social norm|social norms]] and laws that produce misery and suffering.<ref name=\"LernerSimmonsObserver\">{{cite journal |last=Lerner |first=M. |last2=Simmons |first2=C. H. |year=1966 |title=Observer's Reaction to the 'Innocent Victim': Compassion or Rejection? |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=203\u2013210 |doi=10.1037/h0023562 |pmid=5969146 |url=http://web.mit.edu/curhan/www/docs/Articles/biases/4_J_Personality_Social_Psychology_203_(Lerner).pdf}}</ref>\n\nLerner's inquiry was influenced by repeatedly witnessing the tendency of observers to [[victim blaming|blame victims]] for their suffering. During his clinical training as a psychologist, he observed treatment of mentally ill persons by the health care practitioners with whom he worked. Although Lerner knew them to be kindhearted, educated people, they often blamed patients for the patients' own suffering.<ref name=\"LernerFundamental\">{{cite book |last=Lerner |first=Melvin J. |year=1980 |title=The Belief in a Just World: A Fundamental Delusion |series=Perspectives in Social Psychology |location=New York |publisher=Plenum Press |isbn=978-0-306-40495-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4899-0448-5}}</ref> Lerner also describes his surprise at hearing his students [[wikt:derogate|derogate]] (disparage, belittle) the poor, seemingly oblivious to the [[structural violence|structural forces]] that contribute to poverty.<ref name=\"MontadaLernerPreface\" /> In a study on rewards, he observed that when one of two men was chosen at random to receive a reward for a task, that caused him to be more favorably evaluated by observers, even when the observers had been informed that the recipient of the reward was chosen at random.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0033-2909.85.5.1030 | title=Just world research and the attribution process: Looking back and ahead| journal=Psychological Bulletin| volume=85| issue=5| pages=1030\u20131051| year=1978| last1=Lerner| first1=Melvin J.| last2=Miller| first2=Dale T.}}</ref><ref name=\"MaesEightStages\" /> Existing social psychological theories, including [[cognitive dissonance]], could not fully explain these phenomena.<ref name=\"MaesEightStages\">{{Cite book |doi = 10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_10|chapter = Eight Stages in the Development of Research on the Construct of Belief in a Just World?|title = Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World|pages = 163\u2013185|series = Critical Issues in Social Justice|year = 1998|last1 = Maes|first1 = J\u00fcrgen|isbn = 978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> The desire to understand the processes that caused these phenomena led Lerner to conduct his first experiments on what is now called the just-world hypothesis.\n\n==Early evidence==\nIn 1966, Lerner and his colleagues began a series of experiments that used shock paradigms to investigate observer responses to [[victimization]]. In the first of these experiments conducted at the [[University of Kansas]], 72 female participants watched what appeared to be a confederate receiving electrical shocks under a variety of conditions. Initially, these observing participants were upset by the victim's apparent suffering. But as the suffering continued and observers remained unable to intervene, the observers began to reject and devalue the victim. Rejection and devaluation of the victim was greater when the observed suffering was greater. But when participants were told the victim would receive compensation for her suffering, the participants did not derogate the victim.<ref name=\"LernerSimmonsObserver\" /> Lerner and colleagues replicated these findings in subsequent studies, as did other researchers.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\" />\n\n==Theory==\nTo explain these studies' findings, Lerner theorized that there was a prevalent belief in a just world. A just world is one in which actions and conditions have predictable, appropriate consequences. These actions and conditions are typically individuals' behaviors or attributes. The specific conditions that correspond to certain consequences are socially determined by a society's norms and ideologies. Lerner presents the belief in a just world as functional: it maintains the idea that one can influence the world in a predictable way. Belief in a just world functions as a sort of \"contract\" with the world regarding the consequences of behavior. This allows people to plan for the future and engage in effective, goal-driven behavior. Lerner summarized his findings and his theoretical work in his 1980 monograph ''The Belief in a Just World: A Fundamental Delusion''.<ref name=\"LernerFundamental\" />\n\nLerner hypothesized that the belief in a just world is crucially important for people to maintain for their own well-being. But people are confronted daily with evidence that the world is not just: people suffer without apparent cause. Lerner explained that people use strategies to eliminate threats to their belief in a just world. These strategies can be [[Rationality|rational]] or irrational. Rational strategies include accepting the reality of injustice, trying to prevent injustice or provide restitution, and accepting one's own limitations. Non-rational strategies include [[denial]], [[Social withdrawal|withdrawal]], and [[Rationalization (making excuses)|reinterpretation]] of the event.<ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1017/CBO9780511499975.008|chapter = Helping and Rationalization as Alternative Strategies for Restoring the Belief in a Just World: Evidence from Longitudinal Change Analyses|title = The Justice Motive in Everyday Life|pages = 127\u2013148|year = 2002|last1 = Reichle|first1 = Barbara|last2 = Schmitt|first2 = Manfred|isbn = 9780511499975|editor-last=Ross |editor-first=Michael |editor-last2=Miller |editor-first2=Dale T. |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref> \n\nThere are a few modes of reinterpretation that could make an event fit the belief in a just world. One can reinterpret the outcome, the cause, and/or the character of the victim.  In the case of observing the injustice of the suffering of innocent people, one major way to rearrange the cognition of an event is to interpret the victim of suffering as deserving.<ref name=\"An Overview\" /> Specifically, observers can blame victims for their suffering on the basis of their behaviors and/or their characteristics.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\" /> Much psychological research on the belief in a just world has focused on these negative social phenomena of [[victim blaming]] and victim derogation in [[#Additional evidence|different contexts]].<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" />\n\nAn additional effect of this thinking is that individuals experience less personal [[vulnerability]] because they do not believe they have done anything to deserve or cause negative outcomes.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /> This is related to the [[self-serving bias]] observed by social psychologists.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FCdQlTzL-aUC |title = Embitterment: Societal, psychological, and clinical perspectives|isbn = 9783211997413|last1 = Linden|first1 = Michael|last2 = Maercker|first2 = Andreas|date = 2011|location=Wien|publisher=Springer}}</ref>\n\nMany researchers have interpreted just-world beliefs as an example of [[causal attribution]]. In victim blaming, the causes of victimization are attributed to an individual rather than to a situation. Thus, the consequences of belief in a just world may be related to or explained in terms of particular patterns of causal attribution.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.47.3.494 |title = Societal influences on attribution: Blaming some victims more than others|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 47|issue = 3|pages = 494\u2013505|year = 1984|last1 = Howard|first1 = Judith A.}}</ref>\n\n==Alternatives==\n\n===Veridical judgment===\n{{See also|Veridicality}}\nOthers have suggested alternative explanations for the derogation of victims. One suggestion is that derogation effects are based on accurate judgments of a victim's character. In particular, in relation to Lerner's first studies, some have hypothesized that it would be logical for observers to derogate an individual who would allow himself to be shocked without reason.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/h0076786 |title = Devaluation of innocent victims: An attribution analysis within the just world paradigm|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 31|issue = 5|pages = 944\u2013951|year = 1975|last1 = Godfrey|first1 = Bruce W.|last2 = Lowe|first2 = Charles A.}}</ref> A subsequent study by Lerner challenged this alternative hypothesis by showing that individuals are only derogated when they actually suffer; individuals who agreed to undergo suffering but did not were viewed positively.<ref>Lerner, M.J. (1970). The desire for justice and reactions to victims. In J. Macaulay & L. Berkowitz (Eds.), ''Altruism and helping behavior'' (pp. 205\u2013229). New York: Academic Press.</ref>\n\n===Guilt reduction===\nAnother alternative explanation offered for the derogation of victims early in the development of the just-world hypothesis was that observers derogate victims to reduce their own feelings of [[guilt (emotion)|guilt]]. Observers may feel [[Moral responsibility|responsible]], or guilty, for a victim's suffering if they themselves are involved in the situation or experiment. In order to reduce the guilt, they may devalue the victim.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/h0044214 |pmid = 13720212|title = Changes in interpersonal perception as a means of reducing cognitive dissonance|journal = The Journal of Abnormal and Social Psychology|volume = 61|issue = 3|pages = 402\u2013410|year = 1960|last1 = Davis|first1 = Keith E.|last2 = Jones|first2 = Edward E.|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b99153d1428be3bc352ded10335cedc420fb84eb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1467-6494.1964.tb01357.x |pmid = 14238983|title = Changes in liking as a means of reducing cognitive discrepancies between self-esteem and aggression|journal = Journal of Personality|volume = 32|issue = 4|pages = 531\u2013549|year = 1964|last1 = Glass|first1 = David C.|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/37b14d60470b29c030ac7f116cf422e97475a1c6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.33.6.719 |title = Victim derogation in the Lerner paradigm: Just world or just justification?|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 33|issue = 6|pages = 719\u2013724|year = 1976|last1 = Cialdini|first1 = Robert B.|last2 = Kenrick|first2 = Douglas T.|last3 = Hoerig|first3 = James H.}}</ref> Lerner and colleagues claim that there has not been adequate evidence to support this interpretation. They conducted one study that found derogation of victims occurred even by observers who were not implicated in the process of the experiment and thus had no reason to feel guilty.<ref name=\"LernerMillerLooking\" />\n\n===Discomfort reduction===\n\nAlternatively, victim derogation and other strategies may only be ways to alleviate discomfort after viewing suffering. This would mean that the primary motivation is not to restore a belief in a just world, but to reduce discomfort caused by [[empathy|empathizing]].  Studies have shown that victim derogation does not suppress subsequent helping activity and that empathizing with the victim plays a large role when assigning blame. According to [[Ervin Staub]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Staub|first1=Ervin|title=Positive Social Behavior and Morality: Social and Personal Influences, Volume 1|date=1978|publisher=Academic Press Inc.|isbn=978-0-12-663101-2|pages=169\u2013170|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GiOLBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA169&lpg=PA169&q=reduce%20discomfort%20suffering%20erwin%20just%20world}}</ref> devaluing the victim should lead to lesser compensation if restoring belief in a just world was the primary motive; instead, there is virtually no difference in compensation amounts whether the compensation precedes or follows devaluation. [[Psychopathy]] has been linked to the lack of just-world maintaining strategies, possibly due to dampened emotional reactions and lack of empathy.<ref name=\"Hafer2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Hafer |first1=Carolyn L. |last2=B\u00e8gue |first2=Laurent |last3=Choma |first3=Becky L. |last4=Dempsey |first4=Julie L. |title=Belief in a Just World and Commitment to Long-Term Deserved Outcomes |journal=Social Justice Research |date=2005 |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=429\u2013444 |doi=10.1007/s11211-005-8569-3 |url=http://www.lps.univ-savoie.fr/uploads/PDF/576.pdf  |citeseerx=10.1.1.507.4227 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228091123/http://www.lps.univ-savoie.fr/uploads/PDF/576.pdf |archive-date=2013-12-28 }}</ref>\n\n==Additional evidence==\nAfter Lerner's first studies, other researchers replicated these findings in other settings in which individuals are victimized. This work, which began in the 1970s and continues today, has investigated how observers react to victims of random calamities like traffic accidents, as well as rape and [[domestic violence]], illnesses, and poverty.<ref name=\"An Overview\" /> Generally, researchers have found that observers of the suffering of innocent victims tend to both derogate and blame victims for their suffering. Observers thus maintain their belief in a just world by changing their cognitions about the victims' character.<ref>{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_4 | chapter=How do Observers of Victimization Preserve Their Belief in a Just World Cognitively or Actionally?| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=55\u201364| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Reichle| first1=Barbara| last2=Schneider| first2=Angela| last3=Montada| first3=Leo| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s, social psychologists [[Zick Rubin]] and Letitia Anne Peplau developed a measure of belief in a just world.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1973.tb00104.x |title = Belief in a Just World and Reactions to Another's Lot: A Study of Participants in the National Draft Lottery|journal = Journal of Social Issues|volume = 29|issue = 4|pages = 73\u201393|year = 1973|last1 = Rubin|first1 = Zick|last2 = Peplau|first2 = Anne}}</ref> This measure and its revised form published in 1975 allowed for the study of individual differences in just-world beliefs.<ref name = \"RubinPeplau1975\">{{cite journal|last=Rubin |first=Z. |last2=Peplau |first2=L. A. |year=1975  |title=Who believes in a just world? |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=65\u201390 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1975.tb00997.x |url=http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073011/http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 }}</ref> Much of the subsequent research on the just-world hypothesis used these [[psychometrics|measurement scales]].\n\nThese studies on victims of [[#Violence|violence]], [[#Illness|illness]], and [[#Poverty|poverty]] and others like them have provided consistent support for the link between observers' just-world beliefs and their tendency to blame victims for their suffering.<ref name=\"An Overview\" /> As a result, the existence of the just-world hypothesis as a psychological phenomenon has become widely accepted.\n\n===Violence===\nResearchers have looked at how observers react to victims of [[rape]] and other [[violence]]. In a formative experiment on rape and belief in a just world by Linda Carli and colleagues, researchers gave two groups of subjects a narrative about interactions between a man and a woman. The description of the interaction was the same until the end; one group received a narrative that had a neutral ending and the other group received a narrative that ended with the man raping the woman. Subjects judged the rape ending as inevitable and blamed the woman in the narrative for the rape on the basis of her behavior, but not her characteristics.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/0022-1031(85)90013-7 |title = Cognitive biases in blaming the victim|journal = Journal of Experimental Social Psychology|volume = 21|issue = 2|pages = 161\u2013177|year = 1985|last1 = Janoff-Bulman|first1 = Ronnie|last2 = Timko|first2 = Christine|last3 = Carli|first3 = Linda L.|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/223081344}}</ref> These findings have been replicated repeatedly, including using a rape ending and a 'happy ending' (a marriage proposal).<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/01461672992511005 |title = Cognitive Reconstruction, Hindsight, and Reactions to Victims and Perpetrators|journal = Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin|volume = 25|issue = 8|pages = 966\u2013979|year = 1999|last1 = Carli|first1 = Linda L.|citeseerx = 10.1.1.830.8628}}</ref>\n\nOther researchers have found a similar phenomenon for judgments of [[domestic violence|battered partners]]. One study found that observers' labels of blame of female victims of relationship violence increase with the intimacy of the relationship. Observers blamed the perpetrator only in the most significant{{what|date=March 2019}} case of violence, in which a male struck an acquaintance.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1521/jscp.1984.2.4.339|title = Blaming the Victim Versus Blaming the Perpetrator: An Attributional Analysis of Spouse Abuse|journal = Journal of Social and Clinical Psychology|volume = 2|issue = 4|pages = 339\u2013347|year = 1984|last1 = Summers|first1 = Gertrude|last2 = Feldman|first2 = Nina S.}}</ref>\n\n===Bullying===\nResearchers have employed the just-world hypothesis to understand [[bullying]]. Given other research on beliefs in a just world, it would be expected that observers would derogate and blame bullying victims, but the opposite has been found: individuals high in just-world belief have stronger anti-bullying [[Attitude (psychology)|attitudes]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1348/000709909X479105 | pmid=19930790| title=The association between adolescents' beliefs in a just world and their attitudes to victims of bullying| journal=British Journal of Educational Psychology| volume=80| issue=2| pages=183\u2013198| year=2010| last1=Fox| first1=Claire L.| last2=Elder| first2=Tracey.| last3=Gater| first3=Josephine| last4=Johnson| first4=Elizabeth| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3f6e30cf501a02993d86777c4046f1ae0f1541a3}}</ref> Other researchers have found that strong belief in a just world is associated with lower levels of bullying behavior.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1027/1016-9040.13.4.248 |title = School Bullying|journal = European Psychologist|volume = 13|issue = 4|pages = 248\u2013254|year = 2008|last1 = Correia|first1 = Isabel|last2 = Dalbert|first2 = Claudia|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1711694294eef21252ec6d5e3402a556cd25caea}}</ref> This finding is in keeping with Lerner's understanding of belief in a just world as functioning as a \"contract\" that governs behavior.<ref name=\"LernerFundamental\" /> There is additional evidence that belief in a just world is protective of the well-being of children and adolescents in the school environment,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/10615800902729242 |pmid = 19333798|title = Belief in a just world and well-being of bullies, victims and defenders: A study with Portuguese and Indian students|journal = Anxiety, Stress & Coping|volume = 22|issue = 5|pages = 497\u2013508|year = 2009|last1 = Correia|first1 = Isabel|last2 = Kamble|first2 = Shanmukh V.|last3 = Dalbert|first3 = Claudia|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ca1d145496d3740b12fdba4f2b406a7bc173d5f6}}</ref> as has been shown for the [[#Positive health effects|general population]].\n\n===Illness===\nOther researchers have found that observers judge sick people as responsible for their illnesses. One experiment showed that persons suffering from a variety of illnesses were derogated on a measure of attractiveness more than healthy individuals were. In comparison to healthy people, victim derogation was found for persons presenting with indigestion, pneumonia, and stomach cancer. Moreover, derogation was found to be higher for those suffering from more severe illnesses, except for those presenting with cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1207/s15324834basp0401_4 | title=Disease as Justice: Perceptions of the Victims of Physical Illness| journal=Basic and Applied Social Psychology| volume=4| pages=39\u201346| year=1983| last1=Gruman| first1=Jessie C.| last2=Sloan| first2=Richard P.}}</ref> Stronger belief in a just world has also been found to correlate with greater derogation of [[AIDS]] victims.<ref name=\"FurnhamProcterAIDS\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/001872679204500303 |title = Sphere-Specific Just World Beliefs and Attitudes to AIDS|journal = Human Relations|volume = 45|issue = 3|pages = 265\u2013280|year = 1992|last1 = Furnham|first1 = Adrian|last2 = Procter|first2 = Eddie}}</ref>\n\n===Poverty===\nMore recently, researchers have explored how people react to [[poverty]] through the lens of the just-world hypothesis. Strong belief in a just world is associated with blaming the poor, with weak belief in a just world associated with identifying external causes of poverty including world economic systems, [[war]], and [[Exploitation of labour|exploitation]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.2224/sbp.1990.18.2.235 |title = Lay Causal Perceptions of Third World Poverty and the Just World Theory'|journal = Social Behavior and Personality: An International Journal|volume = 18|issue = 2|pages = 235\u2013238|year = 1990|last1 = Harper|first1 = David J.|last2 = Wagstaff|first2 = Graham F.|last3 = Newton|first3 = J. Tim|last4 = Harrison|first4 = Kevin R.|url=http://inesad.edu.bo/developmentroast/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Harper-1990-Poverty-Explanations.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00224545.1992.9712107 |title = The Just World and the Third World: British explanations for poverty abroad|journal = The Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 132|issue = 6|pages = 783\u2013785|year = 1992|last1 = Harper|first1 = David J.|last2 = Manasse|first2 = Paul R.|url=http://psycnet.apa.org/record/1993-29152-001}}</ref>\n\n===The self as victim===\n{{See also|Psychological response to rape|Self blame}}\nSome research on belief in a just world has examined how people react when they themselves are victimized. An early paper by Dr. Ronnie Janoff-Bulman found that rape victims often blame their own behavior, but not their own characteristics, for their [[victimization]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1037/0022-3514.37.10.1798 |pmid = 512837|title = Characterological versus behavioral self-blame: Inquiries into depression and rape|journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume = 37|issue = 10|pages = 1798\u20131809|year = 1979|last1 = Janoff-Bulman|first1 = Ronnie|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cf8f4a1d49479660a825c1ba138b88c5054c9b83}}</ref> It was hypothesized that this may be because blaming one's own behavior makes an event more [[locus of control|controllable]].\n\n==Theoretical refinement==\nSubsequent work on measuring belief in a just world has focused on identifying multiple dimensions of the belief. This work has resulted in the development of new measures of just-world belief and additional research.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /> Hypothesized dimensions of just-world beliefs include belief in an unjust world,<ref>{{cite journal|title= A just and unjust world: Structure and validity of different world beliefs|journal= Personality and Individual Differences|volume= 30|issue= 4|pages= 561\u2013577|doi= 10.1016/S0191-8869(00)00055-6|year= 2001|last1= Dalbert|first1= C.|last2= Lipkus|first2= I.|last3= Sallay|first3= H.|last4= Goch|first4= I.}}</ref> beliefs in [[immanent]] [[justice]] and ultimate justice,<ref>{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_2 | chapter=Immanent justice and ultimate justice: two ways of believing in justice| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=9\u201340| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Maes| first1=J\u00fcrgen| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> hope for justice, and belief in one's ability to reduce injustice.<ref>{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_3 | chapter=BJW and Self-Efficacy in Coping with Observed Victimization| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=41\u201354| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Mohiyeddini| first1=Changiz| last2=Montada| first2=Leo| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref>  Other work has focused on looking at the different domains in which the belief may function; individuals may have different just-world beliefs for the personal domain, the sociopolitical domain, the social domain, etc.<ref name=\"FurnhamProcterAIDS\" /> An especially fruitful distinction is between the belief in a just world for the self (personal) and the belief in a just world for others (general). These distinct beliefs are differentially associated with [[Just-world hypothesis#Positive mental health effects|positive mental health]].<ref name=\"Lipkusetal\" />\n\n==Correlates==\nResearchers have used measures of [[belief]] in a just world to look at correlates of high and low levels of belief in a just world.\n\nLimited studies have examined ideological correlates of the belief in a just world. These studies have found sociopolitical correlates of just-world beliefs, including [[right-wing authoritarianism]] and the [[Protestant work ethic]].{{fix|text=a positive or negative correlation?}}<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/0146167299025006001 | title=Perceptions of Risk and the Buffering Hypothesis: The Role of Just World Beliefs and Right-Wing Authoritarianism| journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin| volume=25| issue=6| pages=643\u2013656| year=1999| last1=Lambert| first1=Alan J.| last2=Burroughs| first2=Thomas| last3=Nguyen| first3=Tina| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/12cd89f3fdf3c59dbaf14f6c746a69be7296e76b}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.2044-8309.1989.tb00880.x |title = Belief in a just world: Review and critique of the individual difference literature|journal = British Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 28|issue = 4|pages = 365\u2013384|year = 1989|last1 = Furnham|first1 = Adrian|last2 = Procter|first2 = Edward}}</ref> Studies have also found belief in a just world to be correlated with aspects of [[religiousness]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Beliefs in justice and faith in people: just world, religiosity and interpersonal trust|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|volume=32|issue=3|pages=375\u2013382|doi=10.1016/S0191-8869(00)00224-5|year=2002|last1=B\u00e8gue|first1=Laurent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kunst |first=J. L. |last2=Bjorck |first2=J. P. |last3=Tan |first3=S.-Y. |year=2000 |title=Causal attributions for uncontrollable negative events |url=http://psycnet.apa.org/record/2000-07654-003 |journal=Journal of Psychology and Christianity |volume=19 |issue=1 |pp=47\u201360}}</ref>\n\nStudies of demographic differences, including [[gender]] and [[Race (classification of humans)|racial]] differences, have not shown systemic differences, but do suggest racial differences, with blacks and African Americans having the lowest levels of belief in a just world.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00224545.1994.9923011 |title = Differences in Assumptions about a Just World: Ethnicity and Point of View|journal = The Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 134|issue = 6|pages = 765\u2013770|year = 1994|last1 = Calhoun|first1 = Lawrence G.|last2 = Cann|first2 = Arnie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 42864385|title = Status, Religion, and the \"Belief in a Just World\": Comparing African Americans, Latinos, and Whites|journal = Social Science Quarterly|volume = 81|issue = 1|pages = 325\u2013343|last1 = Hunt|first1 = Matthew O.|year = 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe development of measures of just-world beliefs has also allowed researchers to assess cross-cultural differences in just-world beliefs. Much research conducted shows that beliefs in a just world are evident cross-culturally. One study tested beliefs in a just world of students in 12 countries. This study found that in countries where the majority of inhabitants are powerless, belief in a just world tends to be weaker than in other countries.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00224545.1993.9712149 |title = Just World Beliefs in Twelve Societies|journal = The Journal of Social Psychology|volume = 133|issue = 3|pages = 317\u2013329|year = 1993|last1 = Furnham|first1 = Adrian}}</ref> This supports the theory of the just-world hypothesis because the powerless have had more personal and societal experiences that provided evidence that the world is not just and predictable.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.2466/pr0.1992.71.3f.1149 | pmid=1480694| title=Relationship between Knowledge of and Attitudes towards Aids| journal=Psychological Reports| volume=71| issue=3_suppl| pages=1149\u20131150| year=1992| last1=Furnham| first1=Adrian}}</ref>{{Clarify|reason=I assume you mean to say 'neither just nor predictable.'|date=February 2014}}\n\nBelief in unjust world has been linked to increased [[self-handicapping]], criminality, defensive coping, anger and perceived future risk. It{{what|date=March 2019}} may also serve as ego-protective belief for certain individuals by justifying maladaptive behavior.<ref name=\"Furnham2003Decade\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lench|first1=Chang|title=Belief in an Unjust World: When Beliefs in a Just World Fail|journal=Journal of Personality Assessment|date=2007|volume=89|issue=2|pages=126\u2013135|doi=10.1080/00223890701468477|pmid=17764390|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a87debcbbdcf9b0d62b160f657ed1d09ff280581}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dolinski|first1=Dariusz|title=The belief in an unjust world: An egotistic delusion|journal=Social Justice Research|date=1996|volume=9|issue=3|pages=213\u2013221|doi=10.1007/BF02197248}}</ref>\n\n==Current research==\n\n===Positive mental health effects===\nAlthough much of the initial work on belief in a just world focused on its negative social effects, other research suggests that belief in a just world is good, and even necessary, for [[mental health]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sbKCnhCPaSgC&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q=%22The%20justice%20motive%20as%20a%20personal%20resource%3A%20dealing%20with%20challenges%20and%20critical%20life%20events%22 |title = The Justice Motive as a Personal Resource: Dealing with Challenges and Critical Life Events|isbn = 9780306465550|last1 = Dalbert|first1 = Claudia|date = 2001|location=New York |publisher=Plenum}}</ref> Belief in a just world is associated with greater [[life satisfaction]] and well-being and less depressive affect.<ref name=\"Lipkusetal\">{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/0146167296227002 | title=The Importance of Distinguishing the Belief in a Just World for Self Versus for Others: Implications for Psychological Well-Being| journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin| volume=22| issue=7| pages=666\u2013677| year=1996| last1=Lipkus| first1=Isaac M.| last2=Dalbert| first2=Claudia| last3=Siegler| first3=Ilene C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.2307/1389045 | jstor=1389045| title=Belief in a Just World and Depression| journal=Sociological Perspectives| volume=33| issue=2| pages=235\u2013252| year=1990| last1=Ritter| first1=Christian| last2=Benson| first2=D. E.| last3=Synder| first3=Clint}}</ref> Researchers are actively exploring the reasons why the belief in a just world might have this relationship to mental health; it has been suggested that such beliefs could be a personal resource or [[coping (psychology)|coping strategy]] that buffers [[Stress (psychological)|stress]] associated with daily life and with [[psychological trauma|traumatic events]].<ref name = \"HaferinMontadaLerner\">{{Cite book | doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5_5 | chapter=Individual Differences in the Belief in a Just World and Responses to Personal Misfortune| title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World| pages=65\u201386| series=Critical Issues in Social Justice| year=1998| last1=Hafer| first1=Carolyn L.| last2=Olson| first2=James M.| isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5|editor-last1= Montada|editor-first1=L.|editor-last2= Lerner |editor-first2=M. J.|location=New York|publisher=Plenum}}</ref> This hypothesis suggests that belief in a just world can be understood as a [[positive illusion]].<ref>{{Cite journal |pmid = 3283814|year = 1988|last1 = Taylor|first1 = S. E.|title = Illusion and well-being: A social psychological perspective on mental health|journal = Psychological Bulletin|volume = 103|issue = 2|pages = 193\u2013210|last2 = Brown|first2 = J. D.|doi = 10.1037/0033-2909.103.2.193|url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/16c6b13d227783a3466d7a0903d9ebb111904502}}</ref>\n\nSome studies also show that beliefs in a just world are correlated with internal [[locus of control]].<ref name=\"RubinPeplau1975\" /> Strong belief in a just world is associated with greater acceptance of and less dissatisfaction with negative events in one's life.<ref name = \"HaferinMontadaLerner\" /> This may be one way in which belief in a just world affects mental health. Others have suggested that this relationship holds only for beliefs in a just world for oneself. Beliefs in a just world for others are related instead to the negative social phenomena of victim blaming and victim derogation observed in other studies.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Justice for all, or just for me? More evidence of the importance of the self-other distinction in just-world beliefs|journal= Personality and Individual Differences|volume= 39|issue= 3|pages= 637\u2013645|doi= 10.1016/j.paid.2005.02.010|year= 2005|last1= Sutton|first1= Robbie M.|last2= Douglas|first2= Karen M.}}</ref>\n\n===International research===\nMore than 40 years after Lerner's seminal work on belief in a just world, researchers continue to study the phenomenon. Work continues primarily in the United States, Europe, Australia, and Asia.<ref name=\"MaesEightStages\" /> Researchers in Germany have contributed disproportionately to recent research.<ref name=\"MontadaLernerPreface\" /> Their work resulted in a volume edited by Lerner and German researcher Leo Montada titled [[#CITEREFMontadaLerner1998|''Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World'' (1998)]].\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*\"[[Best of all possible worlds]]\"\n**[[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz]]\n**''[[Candide]]''\n**[[Problem of evil]]\n*[[Denial]]\n*[[Fundamental attribution error]]\n*[[Hindsight bias]]\n*{{sectionlink|Karma|Comparable concepts}}\n*[[Mean world syndrome]]\n*[[Moral panic]]\n*[[Natural disasters as divine retribution]]\n*[[Revenge]]\n*[[System justification]]\n*[[The banality of evil]]\n*[[Theodicy]]\n*[[Victim blaming]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Hafer |first=C. L. |last2=B\u00e8gue |first2=L.|year=2005 |title=Experimental research on just-world theory: problems, developments, and future challenges |journal=Psychological Bulletin |volume=131 |issue=1 |pages=128\u2013167 |doi=10.1037/0033-2909.131.1.128 |pmid=15631556 |citeseerx=10.1.1.524.1990 }}\n*{{cite book|doi=10.1016/bs.aesp.2014.09.001|chapter=The Why and How of Defending Belief in a Just World|volume=51|pages=41\u201396|title=Advances in Experimental Social Psychology|year=2015|last1=Hafer|first1=Carolyn L.|last2=Rubel|first2=Alicia N.|isbn=9780128022740}}\n*{{cite book |last=Lerner |first=Melvin J. |year=1980 |title=The Belief in a Just World: A Fundamental Delusion |series=Perspectives in Social Psychology |location=New York |publisher=Plenum Press |isbn=978-0-306-40495-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4899-0448-5}}\n*{{cite book |last=Montada |first=Leo |last2=Lerner |first2=Melvin J. |year=1998 |title=Responses to Victimizations and Belief in a Just World |series=Critical Issues in Social Justice |isbn=978-1-4419-3306-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-6418-5|location=New York|publisher=Plenum| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Rubin |first=Z. |last2=Peplau |first2=L. A. |year=1975  |title=Who believes in a just world? |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=65\u201390 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1975.tb00997.x |url=http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073011/http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin%20%26%20Peplau%201975s.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 }} Reprinted (1977) in Reflections, XII(1), 1\u201326.\n*{{cite journal|last=Rubin |first=Z. |last2=Peplau |first2=L. A. |year=1973 |title=Belief in a just world and reactions to another's lot: A study of participants in the national draft lottery |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=73\u201394 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1973.tb00104.x |url=http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin_Peplau_73.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073030/http://www.peplaulab.ucla.edu/Publications_files/Rubin_Peplau_73.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-20 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.units.muohio.edu/psybersite/justworld/index.shtml The Just World Hypothesis]\n*[http://www.scu.edu/ethics/publications/iie/v3n2/justworld.html Issues in Ethics: The Just World Theory]\n\n{{Abuse}}\n{{Biases}}\n{{Bullying}}\n{{Informal fallacy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Just-World Phenomenon}}\n[[Category:Cognitive biases]]\n[[Category:Justice]]\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Conceptual models]]\n[[Category:Hypotheses]]\n[[Category:Abuse]]\n[[Category:Error]]\n[[Category:Ignorance]]\n[[Category:Moral psychology]]\n[[Category:Psychological abuse]]\n[[Category:Informal fallacies]]\n[[Category:Causal fallacies]]\n", "name_user": "Kayaksan", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Just-world_hypothesis"}
{"title_page": "Samurai Jack (comics)", "text_new": "{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> |image = Samurai_Jack_Comics.jpg\n|imagesize           = 238\n|caption             = ''Samurai Jack and the Threads of Time'' #1\n|schedule            = Monthly\n|PostApoc            = n\n|publisher           = [[IDW Publishing]]\n|startmo             = October\n|startyr             = 2013\n|endmo               = May\n|endyr               = 2015\n|issues              = 20 and one special\n|main_char_team      = Jack<br />Aku\n|writers             = [[Jim Zub]]\n|artists             = [[Andy Suriano]]\n|pencillers          =\n|inkers              =\n|letterers           = \n|colorists           = \n|editors             = \n|creative_team_month =\n|creative_team_year  =\n|creators            = [[Genndy Tartakovsky]]<br />[[Jim Zub]]\n|TPB                 = \n|ISBN                = \n|TPB#                =\n|ISBN#               =\n|subcat              = Image Comics\n|altcat              =\n|addpubcat#          =\n}}\n\nThe '''Samurai Jack comics''' was a monthly American comic book series chronicling the travels of Samurai Jack. The comic book series follows up Season 4 of ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' of a time-displaced samurai warrior Jack in his singular quest to find a method of travelling back in time and defeating the tyrannical demon Aku.<ref>{{cite episode|title=II - \"[[The Samurai Called Jack]]\"|series=Samurai Jack|network=Cartoon Network}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, [[IDW Publishing]] announced a partnership with Cartoon Network to produce comics based on its properties. ''Samurai Jack'' was one of the titles announced to be published. It was further announced at [[WonderCon]] 2013 that the first issue of ''Samurai Jack'' will debut in October 2013.<ref>http://www.idwpublishing.com/idw-teams-up-with-cartoon-network/</ref>  The first comic in the series was released October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://read.idwpublishing.com/Samurai-Jack-1/digital-comic/49614 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131123234556/http://read.idwpublishing.com/Samurai-Jack-1/digital-comic/49614 |archivedate=2013-11-23 }}</ref>\n\nNine years after [[Genndy Tartakovsky]]'s series was put on hiatus, and just a few years before [[Adult Swim]] launched [[Samurai Jack (season 5)|its concluding season]], [[IDW Publishing]] had announced a new comic book featuring the continuing adventures of Jack, the temporally displaced warrior and his epic quest to destroy Aku.<ref>[http://www.cartoonbrew.com/comics/jim-zub-and-andy-suriano-reinvent-samurai-jack-for-comics-89951.html Cartoon Brew] Accessed: December 3rd, 2013. | Jim Zub and Andy Suriano Reinvent [[Samurai Jack]]</ref> Beginning with a five-issue storyline called Rope of Eons. Suriano, who designed characters for the show, reflected on returning to the popular character via press release: \"Returning to Samurai Jack is such a personal experience and labor of love for me. It's like stepping through a time portal back to characters I know as friends and a world that really launched my animation career\".\n\nThe first volume, which contained Issues 1\u20135, was released in May 2014. It was made available as both a hard copy and an eBook with a total of 120 pages.<ref>[http://www.jimzub.com/samurai-jack-8-and-vol-1-arrive-in-may/ Samurai Jack: Volume 1] (Issues #1-#5) | Released: May, 2014</ref> Volume 2, \"The Scotsman's Curse\", contains issues 6-10 and was released 28 October 2014.<ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Samurai-Jack-Volume-Scotsmans-Curse/dp/1631401319/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1410855568&sr=8-1&keywords=samurai+jack+volume+2</ref> Volume 3, which highlighted the \"Quest for the Broken Blade\" (Issues 11-15), was officially released on March 31, 2015.<ref>Samurai Jack: Volume 3 ([https://www.amazon.co.uk/Samurai-Jack-Volume-Quest-Broken/dp/1631402455 Quest for the Broken Blade]) on [[Amazon.com]] [Accessed: March, 2015]</ref> Volume 4; \"The Warrior King\", concluding issues 16\u201320, was released on September 1, 2015.<ref>Samurai Jack | [https://www.amazon.co.uk/Samurai-Jack-Warrior-King-Jim-Zub/dp/163140380X/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1430387653&sr=8-1&keywords=sAMURAI+JACK+VOLUME+4 Volume 4: The Warrior King] (Released: September, 2015)</ref>  Over a year later, IDW released a full omnibus compilation of all 20 issues, titled '''''Samurai Jack: Tales of the Wandering Warrior''''', on October 25, 2016.<ref>Samurai Jack | [https://www.amazon.com/Samurai-Jack-Tales-Wandering-Warrior/dp/1631407090 Tales of the Wandering Warrior] (Released: October, 2016)</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Jim Zub, creator of the ''Samurai Jack'' comic series, confirmed that the issues would be concluded with issue #20, in May 2015. He went on to state that \"Working on Jack has been a project that felt just as creative and expansive as any creator-owned work I've done. Almost every single idea we pitched was enthusiastically approved by IDW and Cartoon Network. We told the stories we wanted to tell the way we wanted to tell them and, from everything I\u2019ve seen and the people I\u2019ve met, the fans thoroughly enjoyed them too. That\u2019s a rare and wonderful thing and I won\u2019t take it for granted.\"<ref>[http://www.jimzub.com/samurai-jack-ends-with-issue-20-thoughts-and-thanks/ Samurai Jack Ends with Issue 20] | Jim Zub (Official Website) Accessed: March 2015</ref> Zub wanted fans to feel that with the comics, there is a sense of closure to the series. In the [[List of Samurai Jack episodes#Season 3 .282002.E2.80.932003.29|third season of Samurai Jack]] there's an episode called \u201cJack and Travelling Creatures\u201d where, after trials and tribulations aplenty, we catch a glimpse of a possible future for our wandering hero; we see Jack as an older Warrior-King, a veteran of an untold number of conflicts. Zub stated that the team is \"embracing that awesome vision of Jack in a very heartfelt done-in-one story called 'Mako the Scribe'.\"<ref>http://www.jimzub.com/2015/01/</ref> Tartakovsky does not consider the comics to be [[Canon (fiction)|part of the story of Samurai Jack]].<ref name=\"IGN2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJSvKRuDNrw|title=Samurai Jack Will Cross a Line He's Never Crossed - Comic-Con 2016|publisher=[[IGN]]|author=Joshua Yehl|date=July 25, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017|quote=Tartakovsky: Story-wise, the way they did it isn't, for me, ''Samurai Jack''.}}</ref>{{rp|at=4:58}}\n\nOn 8 May 2019, IDW Publishing released the first series of the '''''Samurai Jack: Lost Worlds''''' comic series. The story looks at how society has prospered under the leadership of the benevolent Samurai Jack and everything is in line with his philosophies after the events of ''Tales of the Wandering Warrior''.<ref>https://butwhythopodcast.com/2019/05/11/review-samurai-jack-lost-worlds-issue-1/</ref> On 20 November 2019, ''Samurai Jack: Lost Worlds'' was compiled into compendium of the four-part series.<ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Samurai-Jack-Worlds-Paul-Allor/dp/1684055520/ref=sr_1_5?crid=QQ11IW0D3NRB&keywords=samurai+jack+comic&qid=1571945192&sprefix=samurai+jack+%2Caps%2C184&sr=8-5</ref> The story was produced by Paul Allor and illustrated by [[Adam Bryce Thomas]]. \n\n==Plot==\n=== Tales of the Wandering Warrior===\n{{Expand section|date=January 2019}}\nThe series is set after the end of the fourth season.  Some time after the events of episode LII, Jack travels through a desert to find a [[hermit]] living in a cave, whom he inquires for a way to return to his own time.  The hermit reveals that Aku learned his mastery of [[time travel]] through an ancient relic known as the Rope of Eons. He studied it, and absorbed its power before destroying it, so others couldn't learn its secrets, although it was possible for one to use the Rope once again if its strands were recovered and assembled together again.  Jack embarks on many quests to reassemble the Rope, only to discover that the last strand was in Aku's possession.  After Jack fights Aku and manages to take the last strand, Aku responds with a fierce attack that mortally wounds Jack, who is then given a choice to either fully sacrifice the Rope's power to undo the fatal blow, or die.  Jack chooses the former, unwilling to lose to Aku, but is forced to escape without accomplishing his goal.\n\nAfter the Rope was lost, Jack reunites with the Scotsman, only to confront a series of supernatural threats, such as the gender-bending curse of the leprechauns, a villain who can manipulate gravity and an attack on his samurai mentality and focus from Aku himself.  He later makes another bid to return to his own time by performing a magic ritual that involved a seer using the spirit of his sword to create a time travel portal, but this backfires and breaks the weapon, leaving Jack unarmed and vulnerable.  When Aku learns of the loss of Jack's sword, he stops at nothing to try and finish off Jack by any means necessary, but Jack manages to escape, stay hidden and survive without his weapon.\n\n===Quantum Jack===\nIn 2017, months after the series was revived and finished with the fifth season, IDW Publishing released a new 5-issue miniseries called \"Quantum Jack,\" which depicts Samurai Jack hopping from one dimension to the next, searching for a way back to his original form as his honor and pride push him forward back to his own time to face Aku one last time. The first issue depicts Jack as the leader of a ruthless biker gang that ambushes a royal convoy. The second issue depicts Jack as a masked luchador. The third issue depicts Jack in a world ruled by monsters known as Krogo, where he teams up with a group of scientists that control a giant battle robot as Jack slowly starts to regain his memory. The fourth issue depicts Jack as a businessman working in a cubicle working for Aku. The fifth and final issue finally reveals how and why Jack has been stranded in time as he makes one last gambit to return to his own time. This series was ultimately collected into a trade paperback.\n\n===Lost Worlds===\nIn 2019, IDW Publishing released a new 4-issue miniseries called \"Lost Worlds,\" which depicts Samurai Jack emerging from his hermetic life to discover a town ruled by a doppelganger of himself, who's determined to conquer the world and spread Jack's philosophies, teachings and beliefs, however, the two Jacks quickly clash as the true nature of the doppelganger is revealed.\n\n==Issues==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" border=\"2\" width=\"100%\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ ''Samurai Jack: Tale of The Wandering Warrior'' comics overview\n|-  style=\"background:#980d26; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"width:50px;\"|Issue No.\n! style=\"width:210px;\"|Issue Title\n! style=\"width:400px;\"|Overview\n! style=\"width:125px;\"|Release Date\n|-\n| 1||Samurai Jack and the Threads of Time||Jack is stranded in a strange future ruled by the demonic wizard, Aku. His quest to return to the past has tested him many times, but now the stakes are higher than ever. Can an ancient relic known as the Rope of Eons finally take him home?<ref>[http://www.comicvine.com/samurai-jack-1-samurai-jack-and-the-threads-of-tim/4000-430790/ Issue 1]: [[Samurai Jack]] - Released: October, 2013</ref>||October 23, 2013\n|-\n| 2||The Threads of Time||Jack can defeat almost any foe in single combat, but how will he fare against a pair of perfectly synchronized warriors who can exploit his every weakness?<ref>http://www.comicvine.com/samurai-jack-2-the-threads-of-time/4000-433872/ Issue 2]: [[Samurai Jack]] - Released: November, 2013</ref>||November 20, 2013\n|-\n| 3||The Threads of Time||Jack's travels bring him to a village filled with tension and mystery. Can he discover the town's strange secret before Aku's robotic army invades? Our samurai hero's quest to gather the Threads of Time continues.<ref>http://www.comicvine.com/samurai-jack-3-the-threads-of-time/4000-437533/ Issue 3]: [[Samurai Jack]] - Released: December, 2013</ref>||December 18, 2013\n|-\n| 4||The Threads of Time||A mystic queen of great power and beauty accepts no criticism, especially from a lowly wandering samurai. Can Jack find another one of the Threads of Time before he's imprisoned for royal heresy?<ref>http://www.jimzub.com/samurai-jack-4-solicitation/ Issue 4]: [[Samurai Jack]] - Released: January, 2014 (On JimZub.com)</ref>||January 22, 2014\n|-\n| 5||The Threads of Time||Martial artists, warriors, nobles, monsters and more... Samurai Jack has defeated them all in his quest to gather the Threads of Time. Now, one last strand remains in the lair of Aku the demon wizard. Can Jack defeat his greatest foe and return to the past?<ref>http://www.jimzub.com/?s=Samurai+Jack+%235 Issue 5]: [[Samurai Jack]] - Released: February, 2014</ref>||February 26, 2014\n|-\n|''Special''||Samurai Jack: Special Director's Cut||Back to the Past! As the evil demon Aku takes over the ancient world, the fate of the world rests in the hands of a noble samurai warrior. But when Aku blasts him into the future, Samurai Jack must find a way to return and right the wrongs of the past! The special Director's Cut reprints the classic adaptation of the first three episodes of ''Samurai Jack'', along with bonus pages and commentary from creator [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] and artist [[William Wray (artist)|Bill Wray]].<ref>[http://www.idwpublishing.com/product/samurai-jack-special-director_zs-cut/ IDWPublishing of Samurai Jack: Director's Cut]</ref>||February, 2014\n|-\n| 6||The Scotsman's Curse||The return of the Scotsman! The humungous highland hooligan and the stoically stalwart samurai team up once again! This time they battle against a bizarre mystic curse that\u2014okay, that part's a secret but trust us, it's a doozy!<ref>http://www.jimzub.com/samurai-jack-6-solicit/ Issue 6]: [[Samurai Jack]] - Released: March, 2014 (On JimZub.com)</ref>||March 19, 2014\n|